    "summary": "The Treaty of Paris of 30 March 1856 ended the [[event:2547|Crimean War]] and represented the most significant reconfiguration of European great-power relationships since the Congress of Vienna. Concluded between Russia on one side and the Ottoman Empire, Britain, France, and Sardinia on the other — with Austria and Prussia as signatories — it imposed terms on Russia that reversed decades of Russian advance into the [[event:94|Ottoman Empire]]'s sphere and attempted to stabilize the crumbling Ottoman state.\n\nThe treaty's key provisions included the neutralization of the Black Sea, prohibiting Russia (and the Ottoman Empire) from maintaining naval forces there — a humiliating restriction on Russian sovereignty in its own southern waters. Russia ceded southern Bessarabia to Moldavia, losing its foothold on the Danube delta. The Danubian Principalities (Moldavia and Wallachia) were placed under collective European guarantee, a step toward Romanian independence. The Ottoman Empire was admitted to the Concert of Europe as a sovereign state, and the signatories collectively pledged to respect its territorial integrity — a guarantee that proved more theoretical than practical in subsequent decades.\n\nThe Black Sea clauses were among the most resented provisions in Russian diplomatic history; Russia renounced them unilaterally in 1870, taking advantage of French defeat in the Franco-Prussian War when no power was willing to enforce them. The broader significance of the Treaty of Paris was to demonstrate both the limits of Russian power and the Ottoman Empire's terminal fragility: the 'Sick Man of Europe' had survived this crisis with external support, but the Eastern Question — who would inherit Ottoman territories in Europe — remained the most dangerous unresolved problem in continental diplomacy until 1914.",
